 Claim: 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 upper triangular and nonsingular iff 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{-1}$
\end_inset

 upper triangular.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 nonsingular implies all diagonal entries of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 are non-zero.
 Therefore for 
\begin_inset Formula $n<m$
\end_inset

 the span of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ r_{1},\dots,r_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore there exist 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{jn}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{1}\rho_{1n}+r_{2}\rho_{2n}+\cdots+r_{n}\rho_{nn}=e_{n}
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{jn}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n<j<\leq m$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
r_{1}\rho_{1n}+r_{2}\rho_{2n}+\cdots+r_{m}\rho_{mn}=e_{n}\label{eq:uppertriang}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Then let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{i}=\begin{bmatrix}\rho_{1i}\\
\vdots\\
\rho_{ii}\\
\vdots\\
\rho_{mi}
\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}\rho_{1i}\\
\vdots\\
\rho_{ii}\\
0\\
\vdots\\
0
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\begin{bmatrix}\rho_{1} & \cdots & \rho_{m}\end{bmatrix}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is upper-triangular since for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 it's the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{jn}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $j=n+1,\cdots,m$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:uppertriang"

\end_inset

 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $R\cdot P=I$
\end_inset

 and by uniqueness of inverses 
\begin_inset Formula $P=R^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 
